{"title_page": "Morgan Ortagus", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{short description|Spokesperson for the U.S. Department of State}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Morgan Ortagus\n|image        = Morgan D. Ortagus.jpg\n|office       = [[Spokesperson for the United States Department of State]]\n|president    = [[Donald Trump]]\n|1blankname  = {{nowr|Secretary}}\n|1namedata   = [[Mike Pompeo]]\n|term_start   = April 3, 2019\n|term_end     = \n|predecessor  = [[Heather Nauert]]\n|successor    = \n|birth_name   = Morgan Deann Ortagus\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1982|7|10}}\n|birth_place  = [[Auburndale, Florida|Auburndale]], [[Florida]], U.S.\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse       = {{marriage|Jonathan Weinberger|2013}}\n|education    = [[Florida Southern College]] ([[Bachelor of Science|BS]])<br>[[Johns Hopkins University]] ([[Master of Arts|MA]], [[Master of Business Administration|MBA]])\n|allegiance   = {{flag|United States}}\n|branch       = {{flag|United States Navy}}\n|serviceyears = 2014\u2013present\n|unit         = [[United States Navy Reserve|U.S. Navy Reserve]]\n}}\n'''Morgan Deann Ortagus''' (born July 10, 1982) is an American government official serving as [[spokesperson for the United States Department of State]] since 2019.<ref name=\"mo1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.state.gov/appointment-of-morgan-ortagus-as-state-department-spokesperson/ |title=Appointment of Morgan Ortagus as State Department Spokesperson |date=April 3, 2019 |publisher=[[United States Department of State|U.S. State Department]] |accessdate=April 3, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"mo2\">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2019/04/02/pompeos-new-spokesperson-bridges-gop-establishment-trump-world/ |last=Rogin |first=Josh |title=Pompeo's new spokeswoman bridges the GOP establishment and Trump world |date=April 2, 2019 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=April 3, 2019}}</ref> She previously held several government positions including Deputy Treasury Attach\u00e9 and [[Office of Intelligence and Analysis (Treasury Department)|Intelligence Analyst]] at the United States Department of the Treasury and Public Affairs Officer at [[United States Agency for International Development|USAID]]. Ortagus worked as national security contributor at [[Fox News]] prior to her appointment as State Department spokesperson.<ref name=\"mo1\" /><ref name=\"mo2\" /> She is also an officer in the [[United States Navy Reserve]].<ref name=\"mo1\" /><ref name=\"mo2\" />\n\n==Early life==\nOrtagus was born in [[Auburndale, Florida]] to Ronald E. and Denise C. Ortagus. Her father owned a cleanup and restoration company and her mother was an [[office manager]]. She grew up in Florida and won the Miss Florida Citrus title in 2002.<ref name=\"mo3\">{{cite web |first=Amrutha |last=Srivatsa |url=https://www.earnthenecklace.com/morgan-ortagus-wiki-facts-fox-news-beauty/ |title=Morgan Ortagus Wiki: Meet Fox News' Impressive Guest Analyst |date=December 11, 2018 |website=EarnTheNecklace.com |accessdate=April 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\nIn 2005, Ortagus graduated from [[Florida Southern College]] with a [[Bachelor of Science]] degree in [[Political science|Political Science]]. In 2013, Ortagus graduated from [[Johns Hopkins University]] (JHU) with a dual [[Master's degree|Master]] degree; [[Master of Business Administration]] from [[Carey Business School|Johns Hopkins Carey Business School]] and [[Master of Arts]] in [[Government]] from JHU. Ortagus's research at JHU included work on [[Counter-insurgency|counterinsurgency]].<ref name=\"mo2\" /><ref name=\"mo3\" />\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Secretary Pompeo Holds Joint Press Availability With Foreign Minister Maas (47971176302).jpg|thumb|Ortagus speaks in Germany in 2019]]\n===Political campaigns===\nIn 2006, Ortagus worked as [[press secretary]] on former [[Deputy National Security Advisor (United States)|Deputy National Security Advisor]] [[K. T. McFarland]]'s [[United States Senate|Senate]] campaign, prior to that she had been a [[campaign staffer]] for Florida Republican congressman [[Adam Putnam]].<ref name=\"mo2\" /><ref name=\"mo3\" />\n\nIn 2016, Ortagus was a [[Campaign volunteer|volunteer]] on [[Jeb Bush]]'s [[Jeb Bush 2016 presidential campaign|presidential campaign]].<ref name=\"mo2\" />\n\n===United States Agency for International Development===\nFrom 2007 to 2008, Ortagus was a public affairs officer at [[United States Agency for International Development]] (USAID) under the [[Presidency of George W. Bush|George W. Bush administration]], spending several months in [[Baghdad]], [[Iraq]]. This was Ortagus's first government service.<ref name=\"mo2\" /><ref name=\"mo3\" />\n\n===United States Department of the Treasury===\nIn 2008, Ortagus joined the [[United States Department of the Treasury|U.S. Treasury Department]], working as an [[Intelligence analysis|Intelligence Analyst]] within the Treasury's Office of Intelligence and Analysis covering [[North Africa]] and [[Middle East]] regions.<ref name=\"mo2\" /><ref name=\"mo3\" />\n\nIn 2010, Ortagus served as Deputy Treasury Attach\u00e9 under the [[Presidency of Barack Obama|Obama administration]] based at the U.S. Embassy in [[Riyadh]], [[Saudi Arabia]] when the [[Arab Spring]] was breaking out within the region. As Deputy Treasury Attach\u00e9, Ortagus worked on countering [[Illicit financial flows|illicit financial flows]].<ref name=\"mo2\" /><ref name=\"mo3\" />\n\n===Private sector===\nAfter returning to the United States, Ortagus left the government and joined the private sector, first as global relationship manager at [[Standard Chartered|Standard Chartered Bank]] working with clients from [[Asia]], the [[Middle East]] and [[Africa]] and then in 2016 as executive director at [[Ernst & Young]] (EY), where she helped found EY's Geostrategic Business Group working on [[Geopolitics|geopolitical]] risk analysis for investors.<ref name=\"mo2\" /><ref name=\"mo3\" />\n\nOrtagus worked as national security contributor and Republican strategist at the [[Fox News Channel]], appearing on ''[[Fox & Friends]]'', ''[[Outnumbered (U.S. TV program)|Outnumbered]]'', ''[[The Five (talk show)|The Five]]'' and ''[[Mornings with Maria]]'' on the [[Fox Business Network]].<ref name=\"mo2\" /><ref name=\"mo3\" />\n\nOrtagus and [[Samantha Vinograd]] are the co-founders of GO Advisors, a geopolitical risk and policy advisory firm.<ref name=\"mo2\" /><ref name=\"mo3\" />\n\n===United States Department of State===\n[[File:Secretary Pompeo Briefs the Traveling Press (48178098606).jpg|thumb|Ortagus with U.S. Secretary of State [[Mike Pompeo]] on July 30, 2019]]\nOrtagus returned to government in 2019 after being appointed Spokesperson for the [[United States Department of State|U.S. State Department]] succeeding [[Heather Nauert]].<ref name=\"mo1\" /><ref name=\"mo2\" />\n\nIn June 2019, Ortagus said the United States \"view [[Canada]]\u2019s claim that the waters of the [[Northwest Passage]] are internal waters of Canada as inconsistent with international law.\"<ref>{{cite news |first=Zo\u00eb |last=Schlanger |title=The US is picking a fight with Canada over a thawing Arctic shipping route |url=https://qz.com/1653831/the-us-is-picking-a-fight-with-canada-over-an-arctic-shipping-route/ |work=[[Quartz (publication)|Quartz]] |date=27 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2019, Ortagus called the [[China|Chinese]] government a \"thuggish regime\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Griffiths |first1=James |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/08/09/politics/hong-kong-china-us-intl-hnk/ |title=US calls China a 'thuggish regime' for 'harassing' Hong Kong-based American diplomat |work=[[CNN]] |date=August 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nOrtagus has been married to Jonathan Weinberger since 2013. [[Associate Justice of the Supreme Court of the United States|Justice]] [[Ruth Bader Ginsburg]] presided over their wedding. This is her second marriage.\n\nWeinberger served as White House associate general counsel and executive secretary on [[Office of the United States Trade Representative|Trade]] from 2008 to 2012 and as executive secretary at the [[U.S. Treasury Department]] from 2003 to 2008.<ref name=\"mo2\" /><ref name=\"mo3\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=224720738&privcapId=4503415 |title=Executive profile: Jonathan R. Weinberger |publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]] |accessdate=April 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* [https://www.state.gov/biographies/morgan-ortagus/ Ortagus, Morgan: Biography]. [[United States Department of State|U.S. State Department]].\n* [https://www.c-span.org/person/?118740 Appearances on C-SPAN]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Heather Nauert]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Spokesperson for the United States Department of State]]|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ortagus, Morgan}}\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:Florida Southern College alumni]]\n[[Category:Fox News people]]\n[[Category:Johns Hopkins Carey Business School alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Auburndale, Florida]]\n[[Category:Florida Republicans]]\n[[Category:Trump administration personnel]]\n[[Category:United States Department of State spokespeople]]\n[[Category:United States Department of State officials]]\n[[Category:United States Department of the Treasury officials]]\n[[Category:United States Navy officers]]\n[[Category:United States Navy reservists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{short description|Spokesperson for the U.S. Department of State}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Morgan Ortagus\n|image        = Morgan D. Ortagus.jpg\n|office       = [[Spokesperson for the United States Department of State]]\n|president    = [[Donald Trump]]\n|1blankname  = {{nowr|Secretary}}\n|1namedata   = [[Mike Pompeo]]\n|term_start   = April 3, 2019\n|term_end     = \n|predecessor  = [[Heather Nauert]]\n|successor    = \n|birth_name   = Morgan Deann Ortagus\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1982|7|10}}\n|birth_place  = [[Auburndale, Florida|Auburndale]], [[Florida]], U.S.\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse       = {{marriage|Jonathan Weinberger|2013}}\n|education    = [[Florida Southern College]] ([[Bachelor of Science|BS]])<br>[[Johns Hopkins University]] ([[Master of Arts|MA]], [[Master of Business Administration|MBA]])\n|allegiance   = {{flag|United States}}\n|branch       = {{flag|United States Navy}}\n|serviceyears = 2014\u2013present\n|unit         = [[United States Navy Reserve|U.S. Navy Reserve]]\n}}\n'''Morgan Deann Ortagus''' (born July 10, 1982) is an American government official serving as [[spokesperson for the United States Department of State]] since 2019.<ref name=\"mo1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.state.gov/appointment-of-morgan-ortagus-as-state-department-spokesperson/ |title=Appointment of Morgan Ortagus as State Department Spokesperson |date=April 3, 2019 |publisher=[[United States Department of State|U.S. State Department]] |accessdate=April 3, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"mo2\">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2019/04/02/pompeos-new-spokesperson-bridges-gop-establishment-trump-world/ |last=Rogin |first=Josh |title=Pompeo's new spokeswoman bridges the GOP establishment and Trump world |date=April 2, 2019 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=April 3, 2019}}</ref> She previously held several government positions including Deputy Treasury Attach\u00e9 and [[Office of Intelligence and Analysis (Treasury Department)|Intelligence Analyst]] at the United States Department of the Treasury and Public Affairs Officer at [[United States Agency for International Development|USAID]]. Ortagus worked as national security contributor at [[Fox News]] prior to her appointment as State Department spokesperson.<ref name=\"mo1\" /><ref name=\"mo2\" /> She is also an officer in the [[United States Navy Reserve]].<ref name=\"mo1\" /><ref name=\"mo2\" />\n\n==Early life==\nOrtagus was born in [[Auburndale, Florida]] to Ronald E. and Denise C. Ortagus. Her father owned a cleanup and restoration company and her mother was an [[office manager]]. She grew up in Florida and won the Miss Florida Citrus title in 2002.<ref name=\"mo3\">{{cite web |first=Amrutha |last=Srivatsa |url=https://www.earnthenecklace.com/morgan-ortagus-wiki-facts-fox-news-beauty/ |title=Morgan Ortagus Wiki: Meet Fox News' Impressive Guest Analyst |date=December 11, 2018 |website=EarnTheNecklace.com |accessdate=April 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\nIn 2005, Ortagus graduated from [[Florida Southern College]] with a [[Bachelor of Science]] degree in [[Political science|Political Science]]. In 2013, Ortagus graduated from [[Johns Hopkins University]] (JHU) with a dual [[Master's degree|Master]] degree; [[Master of Business Administration]] from [[Carey Business School|Johns Hopkins Carey Business School]] and [[Master of Arts]] in [[Government]] from JHU. Ortagus's research at JHU included work on [[Counter-insurgency|counterinsurgency]].<ref name=\"mo2\" /><ref name=\"mo3\" />\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Secretary Pompeo Holds Joint Press Availability With Foreign Minister Maas (47971176302).jpg|thumb|Ortagus speaks in Germany in 2019]]\n===Political campaigns===\nIn 2006, Ortagus worked as [[press secretary]] on former [[Deputy National Security Advisor (United States)|Deputy National Security Advisor]] [[K. T. McFarland]]'s [[United States Senate|Senate]] campaign, prior to that she had been a [[campaign staffer]] for Florida Republican congressman [[Adam Putnam]].<ref name=\"mo2\" /><ref name=\"mo3\" />\n\nIn 2016, Ortagus was a [[Campaign volunteer|volunteer]] on [[Jeb Bush]]'s [[Jeb Bush 2016 presidential campaign|presidential campaign]].<ref name=\"mo2\" />\n\n===United States Agency for International Development===\nFrom 2007 to 2008, Ortagus was a public affairs officer at [[United States Agency for International Development]] (USAID) under the [[Presidency of George W. Bush|George W. Bush administration]], spending several months in [[Baghdad]], [[Iraq]]. This was Ortagus's first government service.<ref name=\"mo2\" /><ref name=\"mo3\" />\n\n===United States Department of the Treasury===\nIn 2008, Ortagus joined the [[United States Department of the Treasury|U.S. Treasury Department]], working as an [[Intelligence analysis|Intelligence Analyst]] within the Treasury's Office of Intelligence and Analysis covering [[North Africa]] and [[Middle East]] regions.<ref name=\"mo2\" /><ref name=\"mo3\" />\n\nIn 2010, Ortagus served as Deputy Treasury Attach\u00e9 under the [[Presidency of Barack Obama|Obama administration]] based at the U.S. Embassy in [[Riyadh]], [[Saudi Arabia]] when the [[Arab Spring]] was breaking out within the region. As Deputy Treasury Attach\u00e9, Ortagus worked on countering [[Illicit financial flows|illicit financial flows]].<ref name=\"mo2\" /><ref name=\"mo3\" />\n\n===Private sector===\nAfter returning to the United States, Ortagus left the government and joined the private sector, first as global relationship manager at [[Standard Chartered|Standard Chartered Bank]] working with clients from [[Asia]], the [[Middle East]] and [[Africa]] and then in 2016 as executive director at [[Ernst & Young]] (EY), where she helped found EY's Geostrategic Business Group working on [[Geopolitics|geopolitical]] risk analysis for investors.<ref name=\"mo2\" /><ref name=\"mo3\" />\n\nOrtagus worked as national security contributor and Republican strategist at the [[Fox News Channel]], appearing on ''[[Fox & Friends]]'', ''[[Outnumbered (U.S. TV program)|Outnumbered]]'', ''[[The Five (talk show)|The Five]]'' and ''[[Mornings with Maria]]'' on the [[Fox Business Network]].<ref name=\"mo2\" /><ref name=\"mo3\" />\n\nOrtagus and [[Samantha Vinograd]] are the co-founders of GO Advisors, a geopolitical risk and policy advisory firm.<ref name=\"mo2\" /><ref name=\"mo3\" />\n\n===United States Department of State===\n[[File:Secretary Pompeo Briefs the Traveling Press (48178098606).jpg|thumb|Ortagus with U.S. Secretary of State [[Mike Pompeo]] on July 30, 2019]]\nOrtagus returned to government in 2019 after being appointed Spokesperson for the [[United States Department of State|U.S. State Department]] succeeding [[Heather Nauert]].<ref name=\"mo1\" /><ref name=\"mo2\" />\n\nIn June 2019, Ortagus said the United States \"view [[Canada]]\u2019s claim that the waters of the [[Northwest Passage]] are internal waters of Canada as inconsistent with international law.\"<ref>{{cite news |first=Zo\u00eb |last=Schlanger |title=The US is picking a fight with Canada over a thawing Arctic shipping route |url=https://qz.com/1653831/the-us-is-picking-a-fight-with-canada-over-an-arctic-shipping-route/ |work=[[Quartz (publication)|Quartz]] |date=27 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2019, Ortagus called the [[China|Chinese]] government a \"thuggish regime\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Griffiths |first1=James |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/08/09/politics/hong-kong-china-us-intl-hnk/ |title=US calls China a 'thuggish regime' for 'harassing' Hong Kong-based American diplomat |work=[[CNN]] |date=August 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nOrtagus has been married to Jonathan Weinberger since 2013. [[Associate Justice of the Supreme Court of the United States|Justice]] [[Ruth Bader Ginsburg]] presided over their wedding. This is her second marriage having previously been married to a man named Josh Dobbs.\n\nWeinberger served as White House associate general counsel and executive secretary on [[Office of the United States Trade Representative|Trade]] from 2008 to 2012 and as executive secretary at the [[U.S. Treasury Department]] from 2003 to 2008.<ref name=\"mo2\" /><ref name=\"mo3\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=224720738&privcapId=4503415 |title=Executive profile: Jonathan R. Weinberger |publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]] |accessdate=April 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* [https://www.state.gov/biographies/morgan-ortagus/ Ortagus, Morgan: Biography]. [[United States Department of State|U.S. State Department]].\n* [https://www.c-span.org/person/?118740 Appearances on C-SPAN]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Heather Nauert]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Spokesperson for the United States Department of State]]|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ortagus, Morgan}}\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:Florida Southern College alumni]]\n[[Category:Fox News people]]\n[[Category:Johns Hopkins Carey Business School alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Auburndale, Florida]]\n[[Category:Florida Republicans]]\n[[Category:Trump administration personnel]]\n[[Category:United States Department of State spokespeople]]\n[[Category:United States Department of State officials]]\n[[Category:United States Department of the Treasury officials]]\n[[Category:United States Navy officers]]\n[[Category:United States Navy reservists]]\n", "name_user": "Editor-1", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePersonal life", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Morgan_Ortagus"}
{"title_page": "Sky burial", "text_new": "{{About|the Tibetan practice}}\n[[File:Sky burial site, Yerpa Valley.JPG|thumb|300x300px|A sky burial site in [[Yerpa]] Valley, [[Tibet]]]]\n[[File:Drigung monastery.jpg|thumb|[[Drigung Monastery]], Tibetan monastery famous for performing sky burials|300x300px]]\n\n'''Sky burial''' ({{bo|t=\u0f56\u0fb1\u0f0b\u0f42\u0f4f\u0f7c\u0f62\u0f0b|w=bya gtor}}, <small>lit.</small>&nbsp;\"bird-scattered\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://people.howstuffworks.com/culture-traditions/cultural-traditions/sky-burial.htm|title=How Sky Burial Works|date=25 July 2011|publisher=}}</ref>) is a [[funeral]] practice in which a human corpse is placed on a mountaintop to [[decompose]] while exposed to the [[mah\u0101bh\u016bta|elements]] or to be eaten by scavenging animals, especially [[Scavenger|carrion birds]]. It is a specific type of the general practice of [[excarnation]]. It is practiced in the region of [[Tibet|Tibet]] and the [[Provinces of China|Chinese provinces and autonomous regions]] of [[Qinghai]], [[Sichuan]] and [[Inner Mongolia]], as well as in [[Mongolia]], [[Bhutan]] and parts of India such as [[Sikkim]] and [[Zanskar]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Sulkowsky|first1=Zoltan|title=Around the World on a Motorcycle|date=2008|publisher=Whitehorse Press|isbn=978-1-884313-55-4|page=114|url=https://octanepress.com/book/around-world-motorcycle}}</ref> The locations of preparation and sky burial are understood in the [[Vajrayana]] [[Buddhism|Buddhist]] traditions as [[charnel ground]]s. Comparable practices are part of [[Zoroastrianism|Zoroastrian]] burial practices where deceased are exposed to the elements and birds of prey on stone structures called [[Dakhma]].<ref>''BBC''. \"[http://www.bbc.co.uk/religion/religions/zoroastrian/ritesrituals/funerals.shtml Zoroastrian funerals Towers of Silence]\". 02 Oct 2009. Accessed 08 Sep 2014.</ref> Few such places remain operational today due to religious marginalisation, urbanisation and the decimation of vulture populations.<ref>''New York Times''. \"[https://www.nytimes.com/2012/11/30/world/asia/cultivating-vultures-to-restore-a-mumbai-ritual.html?_r=0 Giving New Life to Vultures to Restore a Human Ritual of Death]\". 29 Nov 2012. Accessed 08 Sep 2014.</ref><ref>''npr''. \"[https://www.npr.org/2012/09/05/160401322/vanishing-vultures-a-grave-matter-for-indias-parsis Vanishing Vultures A Grave Matter For India's Parsis]\". 05 Sep 2012. Accessed 08 Sep 2014.</ref>\n\nThe majority of [[Tibetan people]] and many [[Mongols]] adhere to [[Vajrayana]] Buddhism, which teaches the [[Rebirth (Buddhism)|transmigration of spirits]]. There is no need to preserve the body, as it is now an empty vessel. Birds may eat it or nature may cause it to decompose. The function of the sky burial is simply to dispose of the remains in as generous a way as possible (the origin of the practice's Tibetan name). In much of Tibet and Qinghai, the ground is too hard and rocky to dig a [[grave]], and due to the scarcity of fuel and timber, sky burials were typically more practical than the traditional [[Buddhist practice]] of [[cremation]]. In the past, cremation was limited to high [[lama]]s and some other dignitaries,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.travelchinaguide.com/cityguides/tibet/sky-buria.htm|title=Sky Burial, Tibetan Religious Ritual, Funeral Party|website=www.travelchinaguide.com}}</ref> but modern technology and difficulties with sky burial have led to an increased use of cremation by commoners.<ref name=dif>''China Daily''. \"[http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/china/2012-12/13/content_16015555.htm Funeral reforms in Tibetan areas]\". 13 Dec 2012. Accessed 18 Jul 2013.</ref>\n\nOther nations which performed air burial were the Caucasus nations of [[Georgians]], [[Abkhazians]] and [[Adyghe people|Adyghe]] people, in which they put the corpse in a hollow tree trunk.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vostlit.info/Texts/rus11/Bagrationi/frametext1.htm|title=\u0418\u0421\u0422\u041e\u0420\u0418\u042f \u0413\u0420\u0423\u0417\u0418\u0418|language=Russian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vostlit.info/Texts/Dokumenty/Kavkaz/XVII/1640-1660/Lamberti/text.htm|title=\u041e\u041f\u0418\u0421\u0410\u041d\u0418\u0415 \u041a\u041e\u041b\u0425\u0418\u0414\u042b \u0418\u041b\u0418 \u041c\u0418\u041d\u0413\u0420\u0415\u041b\u0418\u0418|language=Russian}}</ref>\n\n==History and development==\nThe Tibetan sky-burials appear to have evolved from ancient practices of defleshing corpses as discovered in archeological finds in the region.<ref>PBS. [https://www.pbs.org/programs/cave-people-himalaya/ \"Cave People of the Himalaya\"].</ref> These practices most likely came out of practical considerations,<ref>{{harvnb|Wylie|1965|p=232}}.</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Martin|1996|pp=360\u2013365}}.</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Joyce|Williamson|2003|p=815}}.</ref> but they could also be related to more ceremonial practices similar to the suspected sky burial evidence found at [[G\u00f6bekli Tepe]] (11,500 years [[before present]]) and [[Stonehenge]] (4,500 years BP).{{Citation needed|date=October 2010}} Most of Tibet is above the [[tree line]], and the scarcity of timber makes cremation economically unfeasible. Additionally, subsurface interment is difficult since the [[active layer]] is not more than a few centimeters deep, with solid rock or [[permafrost]] beneath the surface.\n\nThe customs are first recorded in an indigenous 12th-century Buddhist treatise, which is colloquially known as the ''[[Tibetan Book of the Dead|Book of the Dead]]'' ([[Bardo Thodol]]).<ref>{{harvnb|Martin|1991|p=212}}.</ref> Tibetan [[tantra|tantricism]] appears to have influenced the  procedure.<ref>{{harvnb|Ramachandra Rao|1977|p=5}}.</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Wylie|1964}}.</ref> The body is cut up according to instructions given by a lama or adept.<ref name=\"GossKlass\">{{harvnb|Goss|Klass|1997|p=385}}.</ref>\n[[File:Vultures on Lhasa sky burial rock 1.jpg|thumb|300x300px|Vultures feeding on cut pieces of body at a 1985 sky burial in Lhasa, Tibet]]\nMongolians traditionally buried their dead (sometimes with human or animal sacrifice for the wealthier chieftains) but the [[T\u00fcmed]] adopted sky burial following their conversion to Tibetan Buddhism under [[Altan Khan]] during the [[Ming Dynasty]] and other banners subsequently converted under the [[Manchu people|Manchu]] [[Qing Dynasty]].<ref name=hei>Heike, Michel. \"[http://userpage.fu-berlin.de/corff/im/Texte/burial.html The Open-Air Sacrificial Burial of the Mongols]\". Accessed 18 Jul 2013.</ref>\n\nSky burial was initially treated as a primitive superstition and sanitation concern by the [[Communist]] governments of both the [[People's Republic of China|PRC]] and [[Mongolian People's Republic|Mongolia]]; both states closed many temples<ref name=hei/> and China banned the practice completely from the [[Cultural Revolution]] of the late 1960s until the 1980s.<ref name=\"nyt\">{{harvnb|Faison|1999|loc=para. 13}}.</ref> During this period, Sky burials were considered among the [[Four Olds]], which was the umbrella term used by Communists to describe anti-proletarian customs, cultures and ideas. As a result of these policies, many corpses would simply be buried or thrown in rivers. Many families believed the souls of these people would never escape purgatory and became ghosts. Sky burial nonetheless continued to be practiced in rural areas and has even received official protection in recent years. However, the practice continues to diminish for a number of reasons, including restrictions on its practice near urban areas and diminishing numbers of vultures in rural districts. Finally, Tibetan practice holds that the [[yak]] carrying the body to the charnel grounds should be set free{{citation needed|date=November 2017}}, making the rite much more expensive than a service at a [[crematorium]].<ref name=dif/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://english.sina.com/china/2012/1213/537423.html|title=Funeral reforms edge along in Tibetan areas|date=2012-12-13|accessdate=2012-12-16|publisher=Xinhua}}</ref>\n\n==Purpose and meaning==\n[[File:Ragbya carries corps from Lhasa for Sky burial.jpg|thumb|300x300px|Corpse being carried from Lhasa for sky burial about 1920]]\nFor Tibetan Buddhists, sky burial and cremation are templates of instructional teaching on the impermanence of life.<ref name=\"GossKlass\" /> ''Jhator'' is considered an act of generosity on the part of the deceased, since the deceased and his/her surviving relatives are providing food to sustain living beings. Such generosity and [[Karu\u1e47\u0101|compassion]] for all beings are important [[paramita|virtues]] in [[Buddhism]].<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.zmescience.com/other/the-sky-burial/|title = The Sky Burial|date = November 9, 2009|accessdate = January 20, 2015|website = ZME Science|publisher = |last = Mihai|first = Andrei}}</ref>\n\nAlthough some observers have suggested that ''jhator'' is also meant to unite the deceased person with the sky or sacred realm, this does not seem consistent with most of the knowledgeable commentary and eyewitness reports, which indicate that Tibetans believe that at this point life has completely left the body and the body contains nothing more than simple flesh.\n\nOnly people who directly know the deceased usually observe it, when the excarnation happens at night.\n\n==Vajrayana iconography==\nThe tradition and custom of the ''jhator'' afforded [[Traditional Tibetan medicine]] and ''[[thangka]]'' [[iconography]] with a particular insight into the interior workings of the human body. Pieces of the [[human skeleton]] were employed in ritual tools such as the [[Kapala|skullcup]], [[Kangling|thigh-bone trumpet]].\n\nThe 'symbolic bone ornaments' (Skt: {{IAST|a\u1e63\u1e6dhiamudr\u0101}}; Tib: rus pa'i rgyanl phyag rgya) are also known as \"[[mudra]]\" or 'seals'. The ''[[Hevajra Tantra]]'' identifies the Symbolic Bone Ornaments with the [[Five Wisdoms]] and [[Jamgon Kongtrul]] in his commentary to the ''Hevajra Tantra'' explains this further.<ref name=\"Kongtrul_2005_493\">{{harvnb|Kongtrul|2005|p=493}}.</ref>\n\n==Setting==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=February 2009}}\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 135-S-12-50-06, Tibetexpedition, Ragyapa, Geier.jpg|thumb|300x300px|1938 photo of Sky burial from the [[German Federal Archives|Bundesarchiv]]]]\nA traditional ''jhator'' is performed in specified locations in [[Tibet]] (and surrounding areas traditionally occupied by Tibetans). [[Drigung Monastery]] is one of the three most important ''jhator'' sites.\n\nThe procedure takes place on a large flat rock long used for the purpose. The charnel ground (''durtro'') is always higher than its surroundings. It may be very simple, consisting only of the flat rock, or it may be more elaborate, incorporating temples and [[stupa]] (''chorten'' in Tibetan).\n\nRelatives may remain nearby<ref>{{harvnb|Ash|1992|p=59}}.</ref> during the ''jhator'', possibly in a place where they cannot see it directly. The ''jhator'' usually takes place at dawn.\n\nThe full ''jhator'' procedure (as described below) is elaborate and expensive. Those who cannot afford it simply place their deceased on a high rock where the body decomposes or is eaten by birds and animals.\n\nIn 2010, a prominent Tibetan incarnate lama, Metrul Tendzin Gyatso, visited the sky burial site near the [[Larung Gar]] Buddhist Institute in Sertar County, Sichuan, and was dismayed by its poor condition. With the stated goal of restoring dignity to the dead and creating a better environment for the vultures, the lama subsequently rebuilt and improved the platform where bodies are cut up, adding many statues and other carved features around it, and constructed a large parking lot for the convenience of visitors.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://read01.com/a78nP7.html#.XbiyNi-ZNhE|title=\u5587\u69ae\u4e94\u660e\u4f5b\u5b78\u9662\u5c4d\u9640\u6797\uff1a\u5e36\u4f60\u8d70\u9032\u751f\u547d\u8f2a\u8ff4\u7684\u771f\u76f8|date=28 September 2016|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Procedure==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=February 2009}}\nAccounts from observers vary. The following description is assembled from multiple accounts by observers from the U.S. and Europe. References appear at the end.\n\n===Participants===\nPrior to the procedure, [[Tibetan Buddhism#Monasticism|monks]] may chant [[mantra]] around the body and burn juniper [[incense]] \u2013 although ceremonial activities often take place on the preceding day.\n\nThe work of disassembling of the body may be done by a monk, or, more commonly, by ''rogyapas'' (\"body-breakers\").\n\nAll the eyewitness accounts remarked on the fact that the ''rogyapas'' did not perform their task with gravity or ceremony, but rather talked and laughed as during any other type of physical labor. According to Buddhist teaching, this makes it easier for the soul of the deceased to move on from the uncertain plane between life and death onto the next life.\n\nSome accounts refer to individuals who carry out sky burial rituals as a \u2018Tokden\u2019 which is Tibetan for \u2018Sky Burial Master\u2019. While a Tokden has an important role in burial rites, they are often people of low social status and sometimes receive payment from the families of the deceased.\n\n===Disassembling the body===\n[[File:Skyburial.JPG|thumb|A body being prepared for Sky burial in [[Sichuan]]|300x300px]]\n\nAccording to most accounts, vultures are given the whole body. Then, when only the bones remain, these are broken up with mallets, ground with [[tsampa]] (barley flour with tea and [[yak]] butter, or milk), given to the crows and hawks that have waited for the vultures to depart.\n\nIn one account, the leading ''rogyapa'' cut off the limbs and hacked the body to pieces, handing each part to his assistants, who used rocks to pound the flesh and bones together to a pulp, which they mixed with tsampa before the vultures were summoned to eat. In some cases, a Todken will use butcher's tools to divide the body.\n\nSometimes the internal organs were removed and processed separately, but they too were consumed by birds. The hair is removed from the head and may be simply thrown away; at Drigung, it seems, at least some hair is kept in a room of the monastery.\n\nNone of the eyewitness accounts specify which kind of knife is used in the ''jhator''. One source states that it is a \"ritual flaying knife\" or ''trigu'' ([[Sanskrit]] ''[[kartika (knife)|kartika]]''), but another source expresses skepticism, noting that the ''trigu'' is considered a woman's tool (''rogyapas'' seem to be exclusively male).\n\n===Vultures===\n[[File:Vulture - Sky burial.jpg|thumb|Skeletal remains as vultures feed|300x300px]]\nThe species contributing to the ritual are typically the [[griffon vulture|griffon]] and [[Himalayan vulture]]s.\n\nIn places where there are several ''jhator'' offerings each day, the birds sometimes have to be coaxed to eat, which may be accomplished with a ritual dance. If a small number of vultures come down to eat, or if portions of the body are left over after the vultures fly away, or if the body is completely left untouched, it is considered to be a bad omen in Buddhist beliefs.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=MaMing|first=Roller|last2=Lee|first2=Li|last3=Yang|first3=Xiaomin|last4=Buzzard|first4=Paul|date=2018-03-29|title=Vultures and sky burials on the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau|url=https://www.ajol.info/index.php/vulnew/article/view/168874|journal=Vulture News|volume=71|issue=1|pages=22|doi=10.4314/vulnew.v71i1.2|issn=1606-7479|doi-access=free}}</ref>In these cases, according to Buddhist belief, there are negative implications for the individual and/or the individual's family, such as the individual being buried lived a bad life or accumulated bad karma throughout their lifetime and throughout their past lives, thus predetermining them to a bad rebirth.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Gouin|first=Margaret|title=Tibetan Rituals of Death: Buddhist Funerary Practices|publisher=Routledge|year=2010|isbn=9780203849989|location=|pages=70}}</ref>\n\nIn places where fewer bodies are offered, the vultures are more eager, and sometimes have to be fended off with sticks during the initial preparations. Often there is a limit to how many corpses can be consumed at a certain burial site, prompting lamas to find different areas. It is believed that if too many corpses are disposed in a certain burial site, ghosts may appear.\n\nNot only are vultures an important aspect to celestial burial but also to its habitat's ecology. They contribute to carcass removal and nutrient recycling, as they are scavengers of the land.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=MaMing|first=Roller|last2=Xu|first2=Guohua|date=2015-11-12|title=Status and threats to vultures in China|url=http://www.ajol.info/index.php/vulnew/article/view/125620|journal=Vulture News|volume=68|issue=1|pages=10|doi=10.4314/vulnew.v68i1.1|issn=1606-7479|via=|doi-access=free}}</ref> Due to an alarming drop in their population, in 1988, the Law of the People's Republic of China on the Protection of Wildlife added certain species of vultures into the \"rare\" or \"threatened\" categories of their national list of protected wild animals.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=MaMing|first=Roller|last2=Xu|first2=Guohua|date=2015-11-12|title=Status and threats to vultures in China|url=http://www.ajol.info/index.php/vulnew/article/view/125620|journal=Vulture News|volume=68|issue=1|pages=5|doi=10.4314/vulnew.v68i1.1|issn=1606-7479|via=|doi-access=free}}</ref> Local Chinese governments surrounding sky burial locations have established regulations to avoid disturbance of the vultures during these rituals, as well as to not allow individuals who have passed away due to infectious diseases or toxicosis from receiving a sky burial in order to prevent compromising the health of the vultures.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=MaMing|first=Roller|last2=Lee|first2=Li|last3=Yang|first3=Xiaomin|last4=Buzzard|first4=Paul|date=2018-03-29|title=Vultures and sky burials on the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau|url=https://www.ajol.info/index.php/vulnew/article/view/168874|journal=Vulture News|volume=71|issue=1|pages=30|doi=10.4314/vulnew.v71i1.2|issn=1606-7479|via=|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\n==Zoroastrianism==\nAncient [[Zoroastrians]] believed the dead body should be put in a structure called a [[Tower of Silence|Dakhma]] to be feasted upon by birds of prey, because the burial or burning of the corpses would cause water and soil to become dirty, which is forbidden in the ancient religion.\n\n==In popular culture==\nA ''jhator'' was filmed, with permission from the family, for [[Frederique Darragon]]'s documentary ''[[Secret Towers of the Himalayas]],'' which aired on the [[Science Channel]] in fall 2008. The camera work was deliberately careful to never show the body itself, while documenting the procedure, birds, and tools.\n\nThe ritual was featured in films such as  ''[[The Horse Thief]],'' ''[[Kundun]],'' and ''[[Himalaya (film)|Himalaya]].''\n\nA sky burial was shown in BBC's ''[[Human Planet]]'' \u2013 Mountains.\n\nThe semi-autobiographical book ''[[Wolf Totem]]'' discusses sky burial.\n\nSky burials are among the methods of burial discussed in [[Neil Gaiman]]'s ''[[The Sandman: Worlds' End#(#55) \"Cerements\"|The Sandman: Worlds' End]]''.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Disposal of human corpses]]\n* [[Burial tree]]\n* [[Tower of Silence]] or Dakhma, the Zoroastrian structure for exposure of the dead\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{citation|last=Ash|first= Niema|year=1992|title=Flight of the Wind Horse: A Journal into Tibet|pages=57\u201361|publisher=Rider|location=London|isbn=0-7126-3599-8}}.\n* {{citation|last=Bruno|first= Ellen|year=2000|title=Sky Burial&#124;11 minute film|publisher=Bruno Films}}.\n*{{citation|last=Dechen |first=Pemba |year=2012 |title=Rinchen, the Sky-Burial Master |journal=Manoa |volume=24 |pages=92\u2013104 |doi=10.1353/man.2012.0016 |jstor=42004645 |publisher=University of Hawai\u2019i Press}}\n* {{citation |last=Faison |first=Seth |date=July 3, 1999 |chapter=Lirong Journal; Tibetans, and Vultures, Keep Ancient Burial Rite |title=New York Times |publisher=nytimes.com |chapter-url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9A0CE2DB123DF930A35754C0A96F958260&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=all}}.\n* {{citation|last=Goss|first=Robert E.|last2=Klass|first2=Dennis| title=Tibetan Buddhism and the resolution of grief: The Bardo-Thodol for the dying and the grieving|journal=Death Studies|volume=21|issue=4|year=1997|pages=377\u2013395|doi=10.1080/074811897201895|pmid=10170479}}.\n* {{citation|last=Joyce|first=Kelly A.|last2=Williamson|first2=John B.|chapter=Body recycling|title=Handbook of Death & Dying|volume=2|editor-last=Bryant|editor-first=Clifton D.| editor-link= Clifton D. Bryant |isbn=0-7619-2514-7|year=2003|publisher=Sage|location=Thousand Oaks}}.\n* {{citation|last=Kongtrul Lodr\u00f6 Tay\u00e9|first=Jamg\u00f6n|ref=CITEREFKongtrul2005|authorlink=Jamgon Kongtrul<!--|last2=Guarisco|first2=Eliot|last3=McLeod|first3=Ingrid-->|year=2005|title=Systems of Buddhist Tantra, The Indestructible Way of Secret Mantra|series=The Treasury of Knowledge<!--(shes bya kun la khyab pa\u2019i mdzod)-->, book 6, part 4|location=Boulder|publisher=Snow Lion|isbn=1-55939-210-X}}.\n* {{citation|last=Martin|first=Daniel Preston|title=The Emergence of Bon and the Tibetan Polemical Tradition|year=1991|oclc=24266269|series=(Ph.D. thesis)|publisher=Indiana University Press}}.\n* {{citation|last=Martin|first=Daniel Preston|title=On the Cultural Ecology of Sky Burial on the Himalayan Plateau|journal=East and West|volume=46|issue=3\u20134|year=1996|pages=353\u2013370}}.\n*[[Mullin, Glenn H.]] (1998). ''Living in the Face of Death: The Tibetan Tradition''. 2008 reprint: Snow Lion Publications, Ithaca, New York. {{ISBN|978-1-55939-310-2}}.\n* {{citation|last=Ramachandra Rao|first=Saligrama Krishna|title=Tibetan Tantrik Tradition|year=1977|publisher=Arnold Heinemann|location=New Delhi|oclc=5942361}}.\n* {{citation|last=Wylie|first=Turrell V.|year=1964|title=Ro-langs: the Tibetan zombie|journal=History of Religions|volume=4|issue=1|pages=69\u201380|doi=10.1086/462495}}.\n* {{citation|last=Wylie|first=Turrell V.|year=1965|title=Mortuary Customs at Sa-Skya, Tibet|journal=Harvard Journal of Asiatic Studies|volume=25|pages=229\u2013242|doi=10.2307/2718344|jstor=2718344|publisher=Harvard Journal of Asiatic Studies, Vol. 25}}.\n{{refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin}}\n*[http://www.yoniversum.nl/dakini/jhator.html Entry on ''jhator'' in ''Dakini Yogini Central'']\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Sky burial}}\n* [http://www.khandro.net/animal_bird_vulture.htm Eyewitness account], Niema Ash, 1980s\n* [http://www.pamela-logan.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/Survival-and-Evolution-of-Sky-Burial-Practices.pdf Survival and Evolution of Sky Burial Practices in Tibetan Areas of China], Pamela Logan, 2019\n* [http://www.ciolek.com/WWWVLPages/TibPages/tib-burial.html Eyewitness account], Mondo Secter, 1999 - This page also includes references and links to other eyewitness accounts and to a 1986 documentary film that shows a ''jhator''\n* [http://www.keithdowman.net/books/ppct.htm Description of Drigung site], Keith Dowman, orig. pub. 1988\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090514054218/http://bbs.gy.soufun.com/lygs~-1~517/30276306_30276306.htm Photos in Tibet]\n*[http://vimeo.com/24358478 Sky Burial video From TravelTheRoad.com]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BUp4jUMIy68 Sky Burial Footage available on YouTube]\n* {{citation|first=Rachel|last=Laribee|periodical=River Gazette|title=Tibetan Sky Burial: Student Witnesses Reincarnation|date=May 2005|page=9|url=http://www.smcm.edu/rivergazette/articles/05-5-2-9.pdf|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061108091054/http://www.smcm.edu/rivergazette/articles/05-5-2-9.pdf|archivedate=2006-11-08}}.\n{{refend}}\n\n[[Category:Death customs]]\n[[Category:Tibetan culture]]\n[[Category:Tibetan Buddhist practices]]\n[[Category:Birds in religion]]\nthis has no information about where this is published.\n", "text_old": "{{About|the Tibetan practice}}\n[[File:Sky burial site, Yerpa Valley.JPG|thumb|300x300px|A sky burial site in [[Yerpa]] Valley, [[Tibet]]]]\n[[File:Drigung monastery.jpg|thumb|[[Drigung Monastery]], Tibetan monastery famous for performing sky burials|300x300px]]\n\n'''Sky burial''' ({{bo|t=\u0f56\u0fb1\u0f0b\u0f42\u0f4f\u0f7c\u0f62\u0f0b|w=bya gtor}}, <small>lit.</small>&nbsp;\"bird-scattered\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://people.howstuffworks.com/culture-traditions/cultural-traditions/sky-burial.htm|title=How Sky Burial Works|date=25 July 2011|publisher=}}</ref>) is a [[funeral]] practice in which a human corpse is placed on a mountaintop to [[decompose]] while exposed to the [[mah\u0101bh\u016bta|elements]] or to be eaten by scavenging animals, especially [[Scavenger|carrion birds]]. It is a specific type of the general practice of [[excarnation]]. It is practiced in the region of [[Tibet|Tibet]] and the [[Provinces of China|Chinese provinces and autonomous regions]] of [[Qinghai]], [[Sichuan]] and [[Inner Mongolia]], as well as in [[Mongolia]], [[Bhutan]] and parts of India such as [[Sikkim]] and [[Zanskar]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Sulkowsky|first1=Zoltan|title=Around the World on a Motorcycle|date=2008|publisher=Whitehorse Press|isbn=978-1-884313-55-4|page=114|url=https://octanepress.com/book/around-world-motorcycle}}</ref> The locations of preparation and sky burial are understood in the [[Vajrayana]] [[Buddhism|Buddhist]] traditions as [[charnel ground]]s. Comparable practices are part of [[Zoroastrianism|Zoroastrian]] burial practices where deceased are exposed to the elements and birds of prey on stone structures called [[Dakhma]].<ref>''BBC''. \"[http://www.bbc.co.uk/religion/religions/zoroastrian/ritesrituals/funerals.shtml Zoroastrian funerals Towers of Silence]\". 02 Oct 2009. Accessed 08 Sep 2014.</ref> Few such places remain operational today due to religious marginalisation, urbanisation and the decimation of vulture populations.<ref>''New York Times''. \"[https://www.nytimes.com/2012/11/30/world/asia/cultivating-vultures-to-restore-a-mumbai-ritual.html?_r=0 Giving New Life to Vultures to Restore a Human Ritual of Death]\". 29 Nov 2012. Accessed 08 Sep 2014.</ref><ref>''npr''. \"[https://www.npr.org/2012/09/05/160401322/vanishing-vultures-a-grave-matter-for-indias-parsis Vanishing Vultures A Grave Matter For India's Parsis]\". 05 Sep 2012. Accessed 08 Sep 2014.</ref>\n\nThe majority of [[Tibetan people]] and many [[Mongols]] adhere to [[Vajrayana]] Buddhism, which teaches the [[Rebirth (Buddhism)|transmigration of spirits]]. There is no need to preserve the body, as it is now an empty vessel. Birds may eat it or nature may cause it to decompose. The function of the sky burial is simply to dispose of the remains in as generous a way as possible (the origin of the practice's Tibetan name). In much of Tibet and Qinghai, the ground is too hard and rocky to dig a [[grave]], and due to the scarcity of fuel and timber, sky burials were typically more practical than the traditional [[Buddhist practice]] of [[cremation]]. In the past, cremation was limited to high [[lama]]s and some other dignitaries,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.travelchinaguide.com/cityguides/tibet/sky-buria.htm|title=Sky Burial, Tibetan Religious Ritual, Funeral Party|website=www.travelchinaguide.com}}</ref> but modern technology and difficulties with sky burial have led to an increased use of cremation by commoners.<ref name=dif>''China Daily''. \"[http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/china/2012-12/13/content_16015555.htm Funeral reforms in Tibetan areas]\". 13 Dec 2012. Accessed 18 Jul 2013.</ref>\n\nOther nations which performed air burial were the Caucasus nations of [[Georgians]], [[Abkhazians]] and [[Adyghe people|Adyghe]] people, in which they put the corpse in a hollow tree trunk.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vostlit.info/Texts/rus11/Bagrationi/frametext1.htm|title=\u0418\u0421\u0422\u041e\u0420\u0418\u042f \u0413\u0420\u0423\u0417\u0418\u0418|language=Russian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vostlit.info/Texts/Dokumenty/Kavkaz/XVII/1640-1660/Lamberti/text.htm|title=\u041e\u041f\u0418\u0421\u0410\u041d\u0418\u0415 \u041a\u041e\u041b\u0425\u0418\u0414\u042b \u0418\u041b\u0418 \u041c\u0418\u041d\u0413\u0420\u0415\u041b\u0418\u0418|language=Russian}}</ref>\n\n==History and development==\nThe Tibetan sky-burials appear to have evolved from ancient practices of defleshing corpses as discovered in archeological finds in the region.<ref>PBS. [https://www.pbs.org/programs/cave-people-himalaya/ \"Cave People of the Himalaya\"].</ref> These practices most likely came out of practical considerations,<ref>{{harvnb|Wylie|1965|p=232}}.</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Martin|1996|pp=360\u2013365}}.</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Joyce|Williamson|2003|p=815}}.</ref> but they could also be related to more ceremonial practices similar to the suspected sky burial evidence found at [[G\u00f6bekli Tepe]] (11,500 years [[before present]]) and [[Stonehenge]] (4,500 years BP).{{Citation needed|date=October 2010}} Most of Tibet is above the [[tree line]], and the scarcity of timber makes cremation economically unfeasible. Additionally, subsurface interment is difficult since the [[active layer]] is not more than a few centimeters deep, with solid rock or [[permafrost]] beneath the surface.\n\nThe customs are first recorded in an indigenous 12th-century Buddhist treatise, which is colloquially known as the ''[[Tibetan Book of the Dead|Book of the Dead]]'' ([[Bardo Thodol]]).<ref>{{harvnb|Martin|1991|p=212}}.</ref> Tibetan [[tantra|tantricism]] appears to have influenced the  procedure.<ref>{{harvnb|Ramachandra Rao|1977|p=5}}.</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Wylie|1964}}.</ref> The body is cut up according to instructions given by a lama or adept.<ref name=\"GossKlass\">{{harvnb|Goss|Klass|1997|p=385}}.</ref>\n[[File:Vultures on Lhasa sky burial rock 1.jpg|thumb|300x300px|Vultures feeding on cut pieces of body at a 1985 sky burial in Lhasa, Tibet]]\nMongolians traditionally buried their dead (sometimes with human or animal sacrifice for the wealthier chieftains) but the [[T\u00fcmed]] adopted sky burial following their conversion to Tibetan Buddhism under [[Altan Khan]] during the [[Ming Dynasty]] and other banners subsequently converted under the [[Manchu people|Manchu]] [[Qing Dynasty]].<ref name=hei>Heike, Michel. \"[http://userpage.fu-berlin.de/corff/im/Texte/burial.html The Open-Air Sacrificial Burial of the Mongols]\". Accessed 18 Jul 2013.</ref>\n\nSky burial was initially treated as a primitive superstition and sanitation concern by the [[Communist]] governments of both the [[People's Republic of China|PRC]] and [[Mongolian People's Republic|Mongolia]]; both states closed many temples<ref name=hei/> and China banned the practice completely from the [[Cultural Revolution]] of the late 1960s until the 1980s.<ref name=\"nyt\">{{harvnb|Faison|1999|loc=para. 13}}.</ref> During this period, Sky burials were considered among the [[Four Olds]], which was the umbrella term used by Communists to describe anti-proletarian customs, cultures and ideas. As a result of these policies, many corpses would simply be buried or thrown in rivers. Many families believed the souls of these people would never escape purgatory and became ghosts. Sky burial nonetheless continued to be practiced in rural areas and has even received official protection in recent years. However, the practice continues to diminish for a number of reasons, including restrictions on its practice near urban areas and diminishing numbers of vultures in rural districts. Finally, Tibetan practice holds that the [[yak]] carrying the body to the charnel grounds should be set free{{citation needed|date=November 2017}}, making the rite much more expensive than a service at a [[crematorium]].<ref name=dif/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://english.sina.com/china/2012/1213/537423.html|title=Funeral reforms edge along in Tibetan areas|date=2012-12-13|accessdate=2012-12-16|publisher=Xinhua}}</ref>\n\n==Purpose and meaning==\n[[File:Ragbya carries corps from Lhasa for Sky burial.jpg|thumb|300x300px|Corpse being carried from Lhasa for sky burial about 1920]]\nFor Tibetan Buddhists, sky burial and cremation are templates of instructional teaching on the impermanence of life.<ref name=\"GossKlass\" /> ''Jhator'' is considered an act of generosity on the part of the deceased, since the deceased and his/her surviving relatives are providing food to sustain living beings. Such generosity and [[Karu\u1e47\u0101|compassion]] for all beings are important [[paramita|virtues]] in [[Buddhism]].<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.zmescience.com/other/the-sky-burial/|title = The Sky Burial|date = November 9, 2009|accessdate = January 20, 2015|website = ZME Science|publisher = |last = Mihai|first = Andrei}}</ref>\n\nAlthough some observers have suggested that ''jhator'' is also meant to unite the deceased person with the sky or sacred realm, this does not seem consistent with most of the knowledgeable commentary and eyewitness reports, which indicate that Tibetans believe that at this point life has completely left the body and the body contains nothing more than simple flesh.\n\nOnly people who directly know the deceased usually observe it, when the excarnation happens at night.\n\n==Vajrayana iconography==\nThe tradition and custom of the ''jhator'' afforded [[Traditional Tibetan medicine]] and ''[[thangka]]'' [[iconography]] with a particular insight into the interior workings of the human body. Pieces of the [[human skeleton]] were employed in ritual tools such as the [[Kapala|skullcup]], [[Kangling|thigh-bone trumpet]].\n\nThe 'symbolic bone ornaments' (Skt: {{IAST|a\u1e63\u1e6dhiamudr\u0101}}; Tib: rus pa'i rgyanl phyag rgya) are also known as \"[[mudra]]\" or 'seals'. The ''[[Hevajra Tantra]]'' identifies the Symbolic Bone Ornaments with the [[Five Wisdoms]] and [[Jamgon Kongtrul]] in his commentary to the ''Hevajra Tantra'' explains this further.<ref name=\"Kongtrul_2005_493\">{{harvnb|Kongtrul|2005|p=493}}.</ref>\n\n==Setting==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=February 2009}}\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 135-S-12-50-06, Tibetexpedition, Ragyapa, Geier.jpg|thumb|300x300px|1938 photo of Sky burial from the [[German Federal Archives|Bundesarchiv]]]]\nA traditional ''jhator'' is performed in specified locations in [[Tibet]] (and surrounding areas traditionally occupied by Tibetans). [[Drigung Monastery]] is one of the three most important ''jhator'' sites.\n\nThe procedure takes place on a large flat rock long used for the purpose. The charnel ground (''durtro'') is always higher than its surroundings. It may be very simple, consisting only of the flat rock, or it may be more elaborate, incorporating temples and [[stupa]] (''chorten'' in Tibetan).\n\nRelatives may remain nearby<ref>{{harvnb|Ash|1992|p=59}}.</ref> during the ''jhator'', possibly in a place where they cannot see it directly. The ''jhator'' usually takes place at dawn.\n\nThe full ''jhator'' procedure (as described below) is elaborate and expensive. Those who cannot afford it simply place their deceased on a high rock where the body decomposes or is eaten by birds and animals.\n\nIn 2010, a prominent Tibetan incarnate lama, Metrul Tendzin Gyatso, visited the sky burial site near the [[Larung Gar]] Buddhist Institute in Sertar County, Sichuan, and was dismayed by its poor condition. With the stated goal of restoring dignity to the dead and creating a better environment for the vultures, the lama subsequently rebuilt and improved the platform where bodies are cut up, adding many statues and other carved features around it, and constructed a large parking lot for the convenience of visitors.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://read01.com/a78nP7.html#.XbiyNi-ZNhE|title=\u5587\u69ae\u4e94\u660e\u4f5b\u5b78\u9662\u5c4d\u9640\u6797\uff1a\u5e36\u4f60\u8d70\u9032\u751f\u547d\u8f2a\u8ff4\u7684\u771f\u76f8|date=28 September 2016|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Procedure==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=February 2009}}\nAccounts from observers vary. The following description is assembled from multiple accounts by observers from the U.S. and Europe. References appear at the end.\n\n===Participants===\nPrior to the procedure, [[Tibetan Buddhism#Monasticism|monks]] may chant [[mantra]] around the body and burn juniper [[incense]] \u2013 although ceremonial activities often take place on the preceding day.\n\nThe work of disassembling of the body may be done by a monk, or, more commonly, by ''rogyapas'' (\"body-breakers\").\n\nAll the eyewitness accounts remarked on the fact that the ''rogyapas'' did not perform their task with gravity or ceremony, but rather talked and laughed as during any other type of physical labor. According to Buddhist teaching, this makes it easier for the soul of the deceased to move on from the uncertain plane between life and death onto the next life.\n\nSome accounts refer to individuals who carry out sky burial rituals as a \u2018Tokden\u2019 which is Tibetan for \u2018Sky Burial Master\u2019. While a Tokden has an important role in burial rites, they are often people of low social status and sometimes receive payment from the families of the deceased.\n\n===Disassembling the body===\n[[File:Skyburial.JPG|thumb|A body being prepared for Sky burial in [[Sichuan]]|300x300px]]\n\nAccording to most accounts, vultures are given the whole body. Then, when only the bones remain, these are broken up with mallets, ground with [[tsampa]] (barley flour with tea and [[yak]] butter, or milk), given to the crows and hawks that have waited for the vultures to depart.\n\nIn one account, the leading ''rogyapa'' cut off the limbs and hacked the body to pieces, handing each part to his assistants, who used rocks to pound the flesh and bones together to a pulp, which they mixed with tsampa before the vultures were summoned to eat. In some cases, a Todken will use butcher's tools to divide the body.\n\nSometimes the internal organs were removed and processed separately, but they too were consumed by birds. The hair is removed from the head and may be simply thrown away; at Drigung, it seems, at least some hair is kept in a room of the monastery.\n\nNone of the eyewitness accounts specify which kind of knife is used in the ''jhator''. One source states that it is a \"ritual flaying knife\" or ''trigu'' ([[Sanskrit]] ''[[kartika (knife)|kartika]]''), but another source expresses skepticism, noting that the ''trigu'' is considered a woman's tool (''rogyapas'' seem to be exclusively male).\n\n===Vultures===\n[[File:Vulture - Sky burial.jpg|thumb|Skeletal remains as vultures feed|300x300px]]\nThe species contributing to the ritual are typically the [[griffon vulture|griffon]] and [[Himalayan vulture]]s.\n\nIn places where there are several ''jhator'' offerings each day, the birds sometimes have to be coaxed to eat, which may be accomplished with a ritual dance. If a small number of vultures come down to eat, or if portions of the body are left over after the vultures fly away, or if the body is completely left untouched, it is considered to be a bad omen in Buddhist beliefs.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=MaMing|first=Roller|last2=Lee|first2=Li|last3=Yang|first3=Xiaomin|last4=Buzzard|first4=Paul|date=2018-03-29|title=Vultures and sky burials on the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau|url=https://www.ajol.info/index.php/vulnew/article/view/168874|journal=Vulture News|volume=71|issue=1|pages=22|doi=10.4314/vulnew.v71i1.2|issn=1606-7479|doi-access=free}}</ref>In these cases, according to Buddhist belief, there are negative implications for the individual and/or the individual's family, such as the individual being buried lived a bad life or accumulated bad karma throughout their lifetime and throughout their past lives, thus predetermining them to a bad rebirth.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Gouin|first=Margaret|title=Tibetan Rituals of Death: Buddhist Funerary Practices|publisher=Routledge|year=2010|isbn=9780203849989|location=|pages=70}}</ref>\n\nIn places where fewer bodies are offered, the vultures are more eager, and sometimes have to be fended off with sticks during the initial preparations. Often there is a limit to how many corpses can be consumed at a certain burial site, prompting lamas to find different areas. It is believed that if too many corpses are disposed in a certain burial site, ghosts may appear.\n\nNot only are vultures an important aspect to celestial burial but also to its habitat's ecology. They contribute to carcass removal and nutrient recycling, as they are scavengers of the land.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=MaMing|first=Roller|last2=Xu|first2=Guohua|date=2015-11-12|title=Status and threats to vultures in China|url=http://www.ajol.info/index.php/vulnew/article/view/125620|journal=Vulture News|volume=68|issue=1|pages=10|doi=10.4314/vulnew.v68i1.1|issn=1606-7479|via=|doi-access=free}}</ref> Due to an alarming drop in their population, in 1988, the Law of the People's Republic of China on the Protection of Wildlife added certain species of vultures into the \"rare\" or \"threatened\" categories of their national list of protected wild animals.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=MaMing|first=Roller|last2=Xu|first2=Guohua|date=2015-11-12|title=Status and threats to vultures in China|url=http://www.ajol.info/index.php/vulnew/article/view/125620|journal=Vulture News|volume=68|issue=1|pages=5|doi=10.4314/vulnew.v68i1.1|issn=1606-7479|via=|doi-access=free}}</ref> Local Chinese governments surrounding sky burial locations have established regulations to avoid disturbance of the vultures during these rituals, as well as to not allow individuals who have passed away due to infectious diseases or toxicosis from receiving a sky burial in order to prevent compromising the health of the vultures.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=MaMing|first=Roller|last2=Lee|first2=Li|last3=Yang|first3=Xiaomin|last4=Buzzard|first4=Paul|date=2018-03-29|title=Vultures and sky burials on the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau|url=https://www.ajol.info/index.php/vulnew/article/view/168874|journal=Vulture News|volume=71|issue=1|pages=30|doi=10.4314/vulnew.v71i1.2|issn=1606-7479|via=|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\n==Zoroastrianism==\nAncient [[Zoroastrians]] believed the dead body should be put in a structure called a [[Tower of Silence|Dakhma]] to be feasted upon by birds of prey, because the burial or burning of the corpses would cause water and soil to become dirty, which is forbidden in the ancient religion.\n\n==In popular culture==\nA ''jhator'' was filmed, with permission from the family, for [[Frederique Darragon]]'s documentary ''[[Secret Towers of the Himalayas]],'' which aired on the [[Science Channel]] in fall 2008. The camera work was deliberately careful to never show the body itself, while documenting the procedure, birds, and tools.\n\nThe ritual was featured in films such as  ''[[The Horse Thief]],'' ''[[Kundun]],'' and ''[[Himalaya (film)|Himalaya]].''\n\nA sky burial was shown in BBC's ''[[Human Planet]]'' \u2013 Mountains.\n\nThe semi-autobiographical book ''[[Wolf Totem]]'' discusses sky burial.\n\nSky burials are among the methods of burial discussed in [[Neil Gaiman]]'s ''[[The Sandman: Worlds' End#(#55) \"Cerements\"|The Sandman: Worlds' End]]''.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Disposal of human corpses]]\n* [[Burial tree]]\n* [[Tower of Silence]] or Dakhma, the Zoroastrian structure for exposure of the dead\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{citation|last=Ash|first= Niema|year=1992|title=Flight of the Wind Horse: A Journal into Tibet|pages=57\u201361|publisher=Rider|location=London|isbn=0-7126-3599-8}}.\n* {{citation|last=Bruno|first= Ellen|year=2000|title=Sky Burial&#124;11 minute film|publisher=Bruno Films}}.\n*{{citation|last=Dechen |first=Pemba |year=2012 |title=Rinchen, the Sky-Burial Master |journal=Manoa |volume=24 |pages=92\u2013104 |doi=10.1353/man.2012.0016 |jstor=42004645 |publisher=University of Hawai\u2019i Press}}\n* {{citation |last=Faison |first=Seth |date=July 3, 1999 |chapter=Lirong Journal; Tibetans, and Vultures, Keep Ancient Burial Rite |title=New York Times |publisher=nytimes.com |chapter-url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9A0CE2DB123DF930A35754C0A96F958260&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=all}}.\n* {{citation|last=Goss|first=Robert E.|last2=Klass|first2=Dennis| title=Tibetan Buddhism and the resolution of grief: The Bardo-Thodol for the dying and the grieving|journal=Death Studies|volume=21|issue=4|year=1997|pages=377\u2013395|doi=10.1080/074811897201895|pmid=10170479}}.\n* {{citation|last=Joyce|first=Kelly A.|last2=Williamson|first2=John B.|chapter=Body recycling|title=Handbook of Death & Dying|volume=2|editor-last=Bryant|editor-first=Clifton D.| editor-link= Clifton D. Bryant |isbn=0-7619-2514-7|year=2003|publisher=Sage|location=Thousand Oaks}}.\n* {{citation|last=Kongtrul Lodr\u00f6 Tay\u00e9|first=Jamg\u00f6n|ref=CITEREFKongtrul2005|authorlink=Jamgon Kongtrul<!--|last2=Guarisco|first2=Eliot|last3=McLeod|first3=Ingrid-->|year=2005|title=Systems of Buddhist Tantra, The Indestructible Way of Secret Mantra|series=The Treasury of Knowledge<!--(shes bya kun la khyab pa\u2019i mdzod)-->, book 6, part 4|location=Boulder|publisher=Snow Lion|isbn=1-55939-210-X}}.\n* {{citation|last=Martin|first=Daniel Preston|title=The Emergence of Bon and the Tibetan Polemical Tradition|year=1991|oclc=24266269|series=(Ph.D. thesis)|publisher=Indiana University Press}}.\n* {{citation|last=Martin|first=Daniel Preston|title=On the Cultural Ecology of Sky Burial on the Himalayan Plateau|journal=East and West|volume=46|issue=3\u20134|year=1996|pages=353\u2013370}}.\n*[[Mullin, Glenn H.]] (1998). ''Living in the Face of Death: The Tibetan Tradition''. 2008 reprint: Snow Lion Publications, Ithaca, New York. {{ISBN|978-1-55939-310-2}}.\n* {{citation|last=Ramachandra Rao|first=Saligrama Krishna|title=Tibetan Tantrik Tradition|year=1977|publisher=Arnold Heinemann|location=New Delhi|oclc=5942361}}.\n* {{citation|last=Wylie|first=Turrell V.|year=1964|title=Ro-langs: the Tibetan zombie|journal=History of Religions|volume=4|issue=1|pages=69\u201380|doi=10.1086/462495}}.\n* {{citation|last=Wylie|first=Turrell V.|year=1965|title=Mortuary Customs at Sa-Skya, Tibet|journal=Harvard Journal of Asiatic Studies|volume=25|pages=229\u2013242|doi=10.2307/2718344|jstor=2718344|publisher=Harvard Journal of Asiatic Studies, Vol. 25}}.\n{{refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin}}\n*[http://www.yoniversum.nl/dakini/jhator.html Entry on ''jhator'' in ''Dakini Yogini Central'']\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Sky burial}}\n* [http://www.khandro.net/animal_bird_vulture.htm Eyewitness account], Niema Ash, 1980s\n* [http://www.pamela-logan.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/Survival-and-Evolution-of-Sky-Burial-Practices.pdf Survival and Evolution of Sky Burial Practices in Tibetan Areas of China], Pamela Logan, 2019\n* [http://www.ciolek.com/WWWVLPages/TibPages/tib-burial.html Eyewitness account], Mondo Secter, 1999 - This page also includes references and links to other eyewitness accounts and to a 1986 documentary film that shows a ''jhator''\n* [http://www.keithdowman.net/books/ppct.htm Description of Drigung site], Keith Dowman, orig. pub. 1988\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090514054218/http://bbs.gy.soufun.com/lygs~-1~517/30276306_30276306.htm Photos in Tibet]\n*[http://vimeo.com/24358478 Sky Burial video From TravelTheRoad.com]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BUp4jUMIy68 Sky Burial Footage available on YouTube]\n* {{citation|first=Rachel|last=Laribee|periodical=River Gazette|title=Tibetan Sky Burial: Student Witnesses Reincarnation|date=May 2005|page=9|url=http://www.smcm.edu/rivergazette/articles/05-5-2-9.pdf|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061108091054/http://www.smcm.edu/rivergazette/articles/05-5-2-9.pdf|archivedate=2006-11-08}}.\n{{refend}}\n\n[[Category:Death customs]]\n[[Category:Tibetan culture]]\n[[Category:Tibetan Buddhist practices]]\n[[Category:Birds in religion]]\n", "name_user": "114.75.81.112", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eExternal links)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sky_burial"}
